==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|screde||fragment, strip of cloth}} (from which also {{m|en|shred}}<ref name="tow">“Spotlight on... Screed” ''[http://www.takeourword.com/ Take Our Word For It],'' [http://www.takeourword.com/Issue001.html Issue 1], July 20, 1998</ref>), from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|scrēade}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/skɹiːd/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iːd|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A long [[discourse]] or [[harangue]].
#:{{ux|en|One of the more regular correspondents to the club was an Everton fan, who’d send in an abusive '''screed''' each time Albion were due to play on Merseyside. He directed this at Atkinson, urging him not to select his “monkeys” for the game.}} [http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/25/west-brom-three-degrees-book-extract]
# A piece of [[writing]].
# A [[tool]], usually a long strip of wood or other material, for producing a smooth, flat surface on, for example, a [[concrete]] floor or a [[plaster]] wall.
# A smooth flat layer of concrete or similar material.

